<h2>About Christ the Reconciler</h2>
<p>We are a missional community of prayer and reconciliation in Elgin, Texas — sixteen acres of land, a shared household, and a growing network of Christians who believe that the divisions fracturing the Body of Christ are not inevitable.</p>
<p>We are not trying to dissolve our differences. We are trying to end the hostility.</p>

<h2>Who We Are</h2>
<p>Christ the Reconciler is a residential intentional community founded by Thomas and Amy Cogdell, a Protestant-Catholic married couple whose own life together has been a living experiment in the reconciliation they preach.</p>
<p>Our community includes Protestants, Catholics, Orthodox Christians, and Messianic Jews. We don't agree on everything — and we're not trying to. What we share is a common commitment to the prayer of Jesus in John 17: that his people would be one. Not uniform. One.</p>
<p>We gather daily for prayer. We share meals and work. We welcome guests for retreats. We produce teachings and resources for Christians everywhere who are tired of the hostility and ready to do something about it.</p>

<h2>Are We Orthodox? Are We Safe?</h2>
<p>We get it. An ecumenical intentional community can raise eyebrows. So let's be direct.</p>
<p>Christ the Reconciler is rooted in historic, orthodox Christianity. Every member of our community is an active, committed member of their own church, parish, or congregation — Catholic, Protestant, Orthodox, or Messianic Jewish. We do not ask anyone to leave their tradition. We do not create a new denomination. We are not a replacement for your local church.</p>
<p>We affirm the ancient faith shared across the Christian world. Our community members hold real theological differences — and we believe those differences matter and deserve honest engagement, not papering over. What we renounce is not difference, but hostility: the contempt, the dismissiveness, the assumption that a Christian from another tradition is an enemy or a fool.</p>
<p>We have been commended by Catholic priests and Protestant pastors, by Pentecostals and Anabaptists, by leaders in the US and across Europe. <a href="#">Read their words</a></p>

