<h2>What We Believe</h2>
<p>We don't hold a lowest-common-denominator faith. We hold our faiths — Catholic, Protestant, Orthodox, Messianic — and we hold them seriously, with conviction and love.</p>

<p>What brings us together is not agreement on every doctrine. It is a shared conviction that Jesus meant what he prayed, and that Christian hostility is a sin worth repenting of. We believe reconciliation is not a feeling or a metaphor — it is a concrete set of actions that removes hostility, repairs damage, and restores relationship.</p>

<p>The ancient faith of the church — the Trinitarian God, the incarnation, death and resurrection of Jesus, the work of the Holy Spirit — is the ground we stand on together. Beyond that, we hold our differences with honesty and mutual respect, not pretending they don't exist, and not letting them become weapons.</p>

<a href="#"> Our Core Values</a>
<h2>How People Relate to CTR</h2>
<p>One of the most important things to understand about Christ the Reconciler: there is no pressure to go deeper than God is calling you. There are many ways to be part of what we're doing.</p>

<p>Friends, supporters, and distant participants — People who follow along, pray with us, listen to our teachings, and support the work financially. This is wonderful and essential.</p>

<p>Statement of Personal Devotion — Each year, individuals have the opportunity to make a personal commitment to living out John 17 in their own life. This is a meaningful but accessible step, renewed annually, and it doesn't require moving to Elgin. Learn more →</p>

<p>Community Commitment — A deeper level of commitment to living out John 17 together as a community, currently being developed.</p>

<p>Residential Life — When housing is complete, there will be a Residential Rule for those who are called to live here full-time. This is one expression of commitment — not the goal for everyone.</p>

<p>No one is pushed toward the next level. God does that.</p>

